\subsection{Use the \texttt{quadprog} function in Matlab for $L1$ regularization}
\begin{equation}
	\arg \min\limits_{w}\frac{1}{2}(\bm{\Phi w - y})^T(\bm{\Phi w - y}) + \frac{\lambda}{2}\sum\limits_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k|\\
\end{equation}
Which is equivalent to finding:
\begin{equation}
	\arg \min\limits_{w}(\bm{\Phi w - y})^T(\bm{\Phi w - y}) + \lambda\sum\limits_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k|\\
\end{equation}
And expands to:
\begin{equation}
	\arg \min\limits_{w}\bm{w}^T\bm{\Phi}^T\bm{\Phi w} - 2y^T\bm{\Phi w} + \bm{y}^T\bm{y}^T + \lambda\sum\limits_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k|\\
\end{equation}
And for which we can remove the constant term $\bm{y}^T\bm{y}$, yielding:
\begin{equation}
	\arg \min\limits_{w}\bm{w}^T\bm{\Phi}^T\bm{\Phi w - 2y}^T\bm{\Phi w}^T + \lambda\sum\limits_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k|\\
\end{equation}
Matlab's \texttt{quadprog(H, f, A, b)} function, gives the optimal $\bm{x}$ corresponding to the expression 
$\arg\min\limits_{x}  \frac{1}{2}\bm{x}^T\bm{Hx} + \bm{f}^T\bm{x}$,  
subject to constraints 
$\bm{Ax} \leq \bm{b}$. 
We can thus take \texttt{H :=} $2\bm{\Phi}^T\bm{\Phi}$, 
then \texttt{f :=} $2\bm{y}^T\bm{\Phi}$, 
\texttt{A :=}$\lambda \bm{P}$, where for a system with $n$  variables, 
$\bm{P}$ is the matrix with $2^n$ permutations of $[b_1, b_2, \ldots b_n, 0]\footnote{the last zero entry is to avoid the regularization of the intercept term}, b \in \{-1, 1\}$ 
and lastly \texttt{b :=} $c\bm{\stackrel{\rightarrow}{1}}$, 
where$\bm{\stackrel{\rightarrow}{1}}$ is an all-one vector of length $2^n$ that places an upper bound to the 
expression 
$\lambda\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k|$, such that $\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}|w_k| \leq \frac{c}{\lambda}$. 
If we set $c = 1$, then we parametrize $L1$ regularization simply by adjusting $\lambda$ accordingly.
